# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1883-st-louis-browns-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The **1882 major league baseball season** was contested from May 1 through October 2, 1882.
[src:1883-st-louis-browns-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] It was the inaugural season for the American Association (AA) and seventh season for the National League (NL).
[src:1883-st-louis-browns-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The Cincinnati Red Stockings won the AA pennant, while the Chicago White Stockings won the NL pennant.
[src:1883-st-louis-browns-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The American Association was established as a six-team league in cities not represented by the National League.
[src:1883-st-louis-browns-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The AA was established with the expectation that it would have more of a "liberal policy" and better labor relations, threatening the puritanical NL, which itself had formal behavior codes with associated policies and procedures and a blacklist for players who did not comply to said rules.
[src:1883-st-louis-browns-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The AA also refused to recognize the NL's reserve lists.
[src:1883-st-louis-browns-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] Three of the six teams of the American Association survive to this day as National League teams; the Cincinnati Red Stockings, Pittsburgh Alleghenys, and St.
[src:1883-st-louis-browns-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Brown Stockings are today's Cincinnati Reds, Pittsburgh Pirates, and St.
[src:1883-st-louis-browns-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The 1882 season was the last for the Troy Trojans and Worcester Worcesters.
[src:1883-st-louis-browns-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The 1882 schedule consisted of 80 games for all teams in the six-team American Association, and 84 games for all teams in the eight-team National League.
[src:1883-st-louis-browns-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] Each American Association team was scheduled to play 16 games against the other five teams, while each National League was scheduled to play 12 games against the other seven teams.
[src:1883-st-louis-browns-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The 80-game format was unique to the American Association's 1882 season.
[src:1883-st-louis-browns-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] Meanwhile, the National League had been playing their 84-game schedule, since 1879, though 1882 would be their last.
[src:1883-st-louis-browns-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The following season would see both leagues take on a 98-game format, playing 14 games each against their seven opponents.
[src:1883-st-louis-browns-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] National League Opening Day took place on May 1 featuring all eight teams, while American Association Opening Day took place on May 2, featuring all six teams.
[src:1883-st-louis-browns-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The National League would see its final day of the regular season on October 2 featuring a game between the Boston Red Caps and Providence Grays, while the American Association would see its final day of the regular season on October 1, featuring a game between the Louisville Eclipse and St.
[src:1883-st-louis-browns-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] 5 tie games (1 in AA, 4 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again) occurred throughout the season (though in the National League, standings were determined by total wins, not winning percentage).
[src:1883-st-louis-browns-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The Baltimore Orioles and Pittsburgh Alleghenys had one tie game each.
[src:1883-st-louis-browns-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The Detroit Wolverines had three tie games.
[src:1883-st-louis-browns-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The Cleveland Blues and Troy Trojans had two tie games each.
[src:1883-st-louis-browns-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] Any team shown in small text indicates a previous team a player was on during the season.
[src:1883-st-louis-browns-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The Troy Trojans leave Haymakers' Grounds (where they played for two seasons) and move to the Troy Ball Clubs Grounds, where they would play until they folded at the end of the season.
[src:1883-st-louis-browns-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The Troy Trojans continue to host a few games at Riverside Park in nearby Greenbush, New York, playing their first three home games of the season, May 16–18, as well as a fourth game on game 1 of a doubleheader May 30 at the park.
[src:1883-st-louis-browns-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The 1882 season saw three teams play their final games at respective ballparks, before moving to new ballparks for the 1883 season.
[src:1883-st-louis-browns-season/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] Louis Brown Stockings season** was the first professional baseball season played by the team now known as the **St.
[src:1883-st-louis-browns-season/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] It played in the National Association league in 1875 and in the National League from 1876 to 1877.
[src:1883-st-louis-browns-season/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] After a scandal over game-fixing, combined with financial problems, the St Louis Brown Stockings left the National League but continued to play as an independent team from 1878 to 1881.
[src:1883-st-louis-browns-season/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] Chris von der Ahe, a German immigrant, purchased the team prior to the 1882 season and joined the new American Association.
[src:1883-st-louis-browns-season/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] Louis Brown Stockings posted a 37-43 game record in their first season in the American Association, giving them fifth place.
[src:1883-st-louis-browns-season/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] The team played at the Grand Avenue Grounds (which was later renamed Sportsman's Park) at the corner of Grand Avenue and Dodier Street in north St.
[src:1883-st-louis-browns-season/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] Before the 1882 season, Von der Ahe secured a place for the team in the American Association and provided funds to bring players to St.
[src:1883-st-louis-browns-season/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] Between 1882 and 1892, the team he built went on to win four American Association titles.
[src:1883-st-louis-browns-season/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] Al Spink, the team advisor, recommended Von der Ahe sign Charlie Comiskey.
[src:1883-st-louis-browns-season/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] Comiskey, who later played with the Chicago White Sox, was a skilled, young, first baseman who had been playing in Dubuque, Iowa.
[src:1883-st-louis-browns-season/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] Ned Cuthbert was a former professional player in St.
[src:1883-st-louis-browns-season/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] Although he had retired from baseball and worked as a bartender in St.
[src:1883-st-louis-browns-season/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] Louis, Cuthbert remained prominent in the local baseball community.
[src:1883-st-louis-browns-season/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] He had encouraged Von der Ahe to purchase the team.
[src:1883-st-louis-browns-season/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] Von der Ahe hired Cuthbert to be his first captain, with all the duties of a field manager.
[src:1883-st-louis-browns-season/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] Cuthbert used his experience to attract several players to St.
[src:1883-st-louis-browns-season/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] Most of the first-year Browns originated in St.
[src:1883-st-louis-browns-season/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] Louis, including brothers Jack and Bill Gleason, pitcher Jumbo McGinnis, outfielder George Seward, and catcher Tom Sullivan.
[src:1883-st-louis-browns-season/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] In 1866, Gus Solari laid out a professional baseball field at Sportsman's Park, St Louis.
[src:1883-st-louis-browns-season/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] Sixteen years later, on May 2, 1882, the opening day of the St.
[src:1883-st-louis-browns-season/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] Louis Brown Stockings' 1882 season took place.
[src:1883-st-louis-browns-season/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] Approximately 2,000 spectators watched the game for a fee of one quarter each.
[src:1883-st-louis-browns-season/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] The team played numerous local teams in April exhibitions.
[src:1883-st-louis-browns-season/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] McGinnis was the first pitcher and he started 45 of the team's 80 games.
[src:1883-st-louis-browns-season/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] It was a lead off single in the first innings.
[src:1883-st-louis-browns-season/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] He also scored the first run on Comiskey's three-base hit.
[src:1883-st-louis-browns-season/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] The team won their first game with a score of 9 runs to 7.
[src:1883-st-louis-browns-season/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] In late May 1882, the team was in a tie for first place in its six-team league.
[src:1883-st-louis-browns-season/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] They were eight games over .500, putting them one game behind the Cincinnati Reds.
[src:1883-st-louis-browns-season/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] There followed a seven-week period when the team lost sixteen more games than they won.
[src:1883-st-louis-browns-season/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] They could not contend for the championship.
[src:1883-st-louis-browns-season/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] During the season, more than 175,000 spectators attended the team's games.
[src:1883-st-louis-browns-season/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] The favorite players on the team were Comiskey and McGinnis.
[src:1883-st-louis-browns-season/1883-boston-beaneaters-season] The **1883 Boston Beaneaters season** was the 13th season of the franchise.
[src:1883-st-louis-browns-season/1883-boston-beaneaters-season] The Beaneaters won their third National League pennant, their third in six years.
[src:1883-st-louis-browns-season/1883-boston-beaneaters-season] This is also generally recognized as the year during which the team's nickname became the **Boston Beaneaters**.
[src:1883-st-louis-browns-season/1883-buffalo-bisons-season] The **1883 Buffalo Bisons** finished the season with a 52–45 record, good for fifth place in the National League.
[src:1883-st-louis-browns-season/1883-buffalo-bisons-season] Star slugger Dan Brouthers won his second consecutive NL batting title with a .374 average and Pud Galvin posted 46 wins.
[src:1883-st-louis-browns-season/1883-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1883 Chicago White Stockings season** was the 12th season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the eighth in the National League and the sixth at Lakefront Park.
[src:1883-st-louis-browns-season/1883-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings finished second in the National League with a record of 59–39.
[src:1883-st-louis-browns-season/1883-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The **1883 Cincinnati Red Stockings season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:1883-st-louis-browns-season/1883-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The team finished third in the American Association with a record of 61–37, 5 games behind the Philadelphia Athletics.
[src:1883-st-louis-browns-season/1883-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings came into the 1883 season looking to repeat as American Association Champions, as they had a league best record of 55–25 in 1882.
[src:1883-st-louis-browns-season/1883-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] During the off-season, the team announced that catcher Pop Snyder would return as player-manager.
[src:1883-st-louis-browns-season/1883-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Cincinnati also made a big signing, as they signed Charley Jones, who played with the Cincinnati Reds of the National League from 1876–1878.
[src:1883-st-louis-browns-season/1883-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Jones had not played professional baseball since 1880, when he played for the Boston Red Caps of the NL, after which he was black-balled from professional baseball.
[src:1883-st-louis-browns-season/1883-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings also signed another former Reds player, John Reilly, who had also last played major league baseball for the Reds in the 1880 season.
[src:1883-st-louis-browns-season/1883-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] On the diamond, the Red Stockings were led by Jones, who hit .294 with a team leading ten home runs, as well as a league leading 80 RBI.
[src:1883-st-louis-browns-season/1883-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Reilly hit a team high .311 with nine homers and 79 RBI.
[src:1883-st-louis-browns-season/1883-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] On the mound, Will White continued to be the ace of the pitching staff, posting a 43–22 record with 64 complete games and a 2.09 ERA in 577 innings pitched.
[src:1883-st-louis-browns-season/1883-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Cincinnati started off the season on the right foot, winning their first four games, and had an impressive 11–5 record in their first sixteen ballgames.
[src:1883-st-louis-browns-season/1883-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] However, they were 3.5 games behind the Athletics.
[src:1883-st-louis-browns-season/1883-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings would continue to play good baseball, and had a 31–23 record.
[src:1883-st-louis-browns-season/1883-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Cincinnati would then go on to win twelve of their next thirteen games to improve to 43–24.
[src:1883-st-louis-browns-season/1883-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] However, they only moved up to third place.
[src:1883-st-louis-browns-season/1883-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings would remain in third place for the rest of the season, finishing the year at 61–37, five games behind the Athletics.
[src:1883-st-louis-browns-season/1883-st-louis-browns-season] Louis Browns season** was the team's second season in St.
[src:1883-st-louis-browns-season/1883-st-louis-browns-season] Louis, Missouri and its second season in the American Association.
[src:1883-st-louis-browns-season/1883-st-louis-browns-season] The Browns went 65–33 during the season and finished second in the American Association.
